    },
    {
      "_type": "block",
      "style": "normal",
      "children": [
        {
          "_type": "span",
          "text": "Opportunity cost is classically defined as ‘the highest-valued alternative that must be sacrificed when we make a decision.’ But it’s better understood as ",
          "marks": []
        },
        {
          "_type": "span",
          "text": "all",
          "marks": []
        },
        {
          "_type": "span",
          "text": " the alternative opportunities you pass up by making a choice. Thing is, we’ll never know what ",
          "marks": []
        },
        {
          "_type": "span",
          "text": "all",
          "marks": []
        },
        {
          "_type": "span",
          "text": " the opportunity costs are for any one choice that we make. And it’s a mistake to assume that—just because the result of one outcome is easier to measure—it’s somehow ",
          "marks": []
        },
        {
          "_type": "span",
          "text": "more",
          "marks": []
        },
        {
          "_type": "span",
          "text": " costly.",
          "marks": []
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "_type": "block",
      "style": "normal",
      "children": [
        {
          "_type": "span",
          "text": "Costs are relative. As is ",
          "marks": []
        },
        {
          "_type": "span",
          "text": "value",
          "marks": [
            "link-0"
          ]
        },
        {
          "_type": "span",
          "text": ". So making a decision based on an objective, easily-assessed standard is likely not the best method.",
          "marks": []
        }
